accesses.location: Two dead end roads; N end of lake.

surveys.narrative: Tanners Lake is almost within the limits of Ramsey County in western Washington County. It must be considered one of the Metropolitan lakes, yet recorded public access is lacking. It is physically fit for bass, panfish, and northern pike which presently inhabit the lake. The walleye stocking of prior years seems to have had little effect though numbers are still present in the lake. The encouragement of northern pike appears to be the single, most important management action needed.

Although the present gamefish population is quite low, management of this lake for bass and panfish would do the most good. Any success of this type of management will depend first on removal of excess numbers of bullheads.Bullheads need removal. Past experience indicates that at least 100 lbs. per acre per year need to be removed to reduce the population sufficiently so that game fishes might better survive.

Northern pike were sampled at higher than average numbers. The fish sampled were small average size but exhibited average growth for the area. Bluegill were sampled at an average rate for the area with the fish sampled being average or slightly above average size. Yellow perch were sampled in average numbers and appeared to be average sized. Walleye were sampled in average abundance for the area, but were all from the 1986 year class. The walleye sampled exhibited average growth for the area. All additional species sampled were taken in low numbers.

Bluegills, pumpkinseeds, and hybrid sunfish were found well above state and local median catches. Black bullheads, yellow bullheads, black crappies, and largemouth bass were found near the median levels and white sucker, northern pike, yellow perch, walleye, and golden shiners were found to be below median catches. Carp are known to inhabit the lake.

Bluegills are the most abundant species in Tanners Lake. The population is considered average when comparing similar lakes. The average size found was 5.26 inches. Only 27.8% of the bluegills sampled exceeded 6 inches in length. Black crappies were also sampled in average abundance. Their average size was 6.17 inches. Only 2 walleye were sampled during this survey and were both stocked the previous year. Neither fish exceeded 12 inches in length. Northern pike were sampled in average abundance and size. Individuals up to 27 inches were sampled during the survey. Pumpkinseed sunfish, green sunfish and hybrid sunfish were each sampled in average numbers. Channel catfish were not sampled during this survey. Annual stocking of this species continues

The August data for Tanners Lake indicates that high populations of northern pike, yellow perch, bluegill, and hybrid sunfish exist. Black crappie numbers are low and average numbers of white sucker, yellow bullhead, and pumpkinseed are found in Tanners Lake. Northern pike numbers give indication of an increase since 1975 although direct comparison is not possible. The last stocking conducted was 1976. The current length frequency would tend to indicate that at least a portion of the catch is made up of naturally reproduced fish. Yellow bullhead were taken only in gillnets (1 fish) in 1975 while in 1980 they were more numerous being taken in both gill and trap nets. Brown bullhead show the reverse, being taken in good numbers in the 1975 trapnets but absent in the 1980 netting. Bluegill numbers remain high with small fish predominating. Largemouth bass reproduction is verified from shoreling seining results.

The gillnet survey was conducted to assess the walleye population resulting from the initiating of a walleye stocking program including stocking 276 adult walleyes i spring 1987. Walleye fingerlings were stocked in fall 1986. The small size of Tanners Lake and a newly developed access allowed a unique opportunity to stock walleye adults at 10 fish per littoral acre and evaluate survival after a period of fishing. Walleyes sampled were mostly from the 1986 fingerling stocking. Survival and growth are good. Three walleye adults were netted. They were of the 1985 yearclass and exhibited normal growth. Fishing for the stocked adults was reported to be very good. Northern pike sampled showed good average growth and size distribution. There is ample perch forage available for both northern pike and walleye.

Yellow perch, brown bullhead, bluegill, and black crappie are each above their respective statewide medians in number and pounds per set. White sucker, northern pike, and black bullhead are each below their respective medians in number and pounds per set. The precise abundance of pumpkinseed, green sunfish, and hybrid sunfish cannot be determined, since they were lumped together (listed as "pumpkinseed" in length-frequency data).

Bluegills are the most abundant species in Tanners Lake. The population is considered average when comparing similar lakes. The average size found was 5.34 inches. Only 24% of the bluegills sampled were larger than 6 inches. Black crappies were sampled in low abundance and small size, 6.4 inches. Walleye were found in moderate numbers and size, 16 inches. Northern pike abundance is low but the average size sampled, 26.4 inches, is above the metro average. Channel catfish have been stocked since 1996. The population has increased each successive survey. Individuals up to 22.8 inches were sampled. Largemouth bass were sampled in good abundance and a variety of sizes. Individuals up to 16.8 inches in length were found. Pumpkinseed sunfish were found in high abundance for this type of lake. Green sunfish and hybrid sunfish were found in average abundance. Black bullhead were sampled in low numbers, while yellow bullhead were sampled in average numbers.

Tanners Lake is a small lake (70 acres) located on the north side of I-94, east of Century Avenue. Surface use ordinance limits speeds on the lake to 10 mph or less.Bluegill, hybrid, and pumpkinseed sunfish dominated the catch. Most fish were small, although a few bluegill were over 7 inches long. Black crappie numbers, after reaching historic highs in 1995, dropped to low levels. Fish were small, with few over 8 inches. Yellow perch were moderately abundant and small in size.Northern pike, largemouth bass, and walleye were present in low numbers. Channel catfish were sampled for the first time in this lake, with fish ranging from 14-17 inches long. Yellow bullhead, white sucker, and black bullhead were also sampled in low numbers.

Bluegill numbers were much lower than ten years ago. Fish were small, with a tenth of acceptable size to anglers. Black crappie numbers are at an all time high, with fish small in size. Northern pike numbers were moderate with over a tenth of good size. Fish were young and fast growing. Walleye numbers were fair with most fish over 16 inches in length. Good numbers of young largemouth bass were sampled. Electrofishing was not done to assess the adult population. Yellow perch were common with fish of small size. A few yellow bullhead were sampled with several large individuals present. Three white sucker, three giolden shiner, and one black bullhead were also sampled.
